a:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"JWST identifies new exoplanet category"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Atmospheric chemistry drives classification"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Observation demonstrates telescope capabilities"}]]}]]}]}]
b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["The James Webb Space Telescope has identified what astronomers are calling a new class of exoplanet, according to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.space.com","children":"Space.com"}],". This matters not because of the unusual characterization that the planet \"probably smells like rotten eggs,\" but because JWST's instruments have detected atmospheric signatures distinctive enough to warrant an entirely new classification category. The discovery represents a significant milestone in ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nasa.gov/webb","children":"JWST's exoplanet characterization mission"}],", demonstrating the telescope's capacity to analyze atmospheric compositions with precision that was simply impossible before its deployment. Early signals suggest the presence of sulfur compounds, which would explain the pungent comparison, though researchers have not yet confirmed the exact molecular makeup. What's notable here is the methodical approach. This wasn't a serendipitous find but the result of systematic atmospheric analysis that JWST was specifically designed to conduct."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/jwst-discovers-new-exoplanet-class-with-distinctiv/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the data actually confirms","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"What the data actually confirms"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The scientific significance lies in what this reveals about planetary diversity. Until now, exoplanets fell into established categories based largely on size and orbital characteristics. This discovery suggests atmospheric chemistry may deserve equal weight in classification schemes. Mission context matters. JWST has been operational for over two years, and this finding emerges from its extended survey phase. The telescope's primary mission objectives included characterizing exoplanet atmospheres, but identifying entirely new planetary classes represents an outcome that exceeded baseline expectations. What remains uncertain is the precise atmospheric composition. While the \"rotten egg\" description has captured attention, researchers have not released detailed spectroscopic analyses. The ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://webb.nasa.gov","children":"James Webb mission team"}]," will likely follow up with additional observations to confirm the molecular signatures. For planetary science, the implications extend beyond this single object, ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.space.com/james-webb-space-telescope","children":"according to early interpretation"}],"."]}]]}]
